There is a method called `getch()` that reads a single character from the standard input. It returns a `char` value, or -1 if it fails to read anything. It is part of the standard C library. You can find it in the header file `<cstdio>`.

The C++ standard library has a similar function called `getchar()`, which has a different calling convention. It is defined in the header file `<stdlib.h>` instead of `<cstdio>`. You can use either function to read a single character, but make sure to use the right one for each platform.

The Windows API has a function called `ReadConsoleInput` that reads characters from a keyboard in a loop, rather than returning just one at a time. You can use this to read keys pressed by a user, and determine if they pressed the key you are looking for. However, it is not as fast as `getch` and `getchar`, so it should only be used when you need to process multiple keystrokes at once.

Here is an example of how you could use `ReadConsoleInput` in C:
```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <windows.h>
int main() {
    HANDLE hStdIn = GetStdHandle(STD_INPUT_HANDLE);
    CONSOLE_SCREEN_BUFFER_INFO csbi;
    DWORD dwRead = 0;
    DWORD dwReadCount = 0;
    do {
        DWORD n = ReadConsoleInput(hStdIn, &csbi, 1, &dwReadCount);
        if (n != 0) {
            DWORD nRet = ReadConsoleOutputCharacter(hStdIn, &csbi.wValue[dwRead], 1);
            if (nRet != 0) {
                // This character was read, but it's not what we're looking for... move on!
                dwRead++;
                continue; // retry ReadConsoleInput() next time around the loop!
            } else {
                // This character was NOT read because we didn't have enough time or buffer space... move on! 
                dwReadCount++; // increase count of characters attempted to read! 
            }
        } else {  // No characters were read because there was nothing new to read! 
            break; // exit loop!  
        }    
    } while (dwReadCount > 0); // keep reading until there are no more chars left to read!  
    return EXIT_SUCCESS; // return success code...   ...unless there was an error!  
}   /* main() */  
```

